struct platform_device:
=======================

name: Identifier for the device, a string.
id: Instance number to differentiate devices with the same name, an integer.
dev: Core structure representing the device in the kernel.


struct device (dev within platform_device):
==========================================
parent: Points to the parent device in the device hierarchy.
driver: Links to the device_driver responsible for this device.
driver_data: Holds data set by the driver, a pointer to void.
bus: Type of bus the device is attached to.
power: Power-related information of the device, including state and wakeup capabilities.
groups: Attribute groups for creating sysfs entries.
release: Callback when the device's reference count reaches zero.
of_node: Points to the corresponding device tree node.

struct device_driver:
=====================
Functions that the driver provides for device operations 
such as probe, remove, shutdown, suspend, and resume.

struct bus_type:
===============
name: Name of the bus type.

struct resource:
=================
Describes I/O memory regions, IRQs, and DMA channels, including start and end addresses, type, and hierarchy links.

struct device_node (of_node in device):
=======================================
Represents the node in the device tree.


Open-firmware API
=================

Kernel drivers frequently use a set of APIs to interact with device tree nodes
enabling them to retrieve configuration information directly from the device tree. 

Here’s a summarized list of commonly used device tree node APIs by kernel drivers:

+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| API                                | Description                                               | Kernel Header                     |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_find_node_by_path()             | Finds a device tree node by its path.                     | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_find_compatible_node()          | Locates a node that matches a compatible property.        | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_property_read_u32()             | Reads a 32-bit unsigned integer from a property.          | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_property_read_u32_array()       | Reads an array of 32-bit unsigned integers from a property.| <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_property_read_string()          | Reads a string from a property.                           | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_parse_phandle()                 | Retrieves the `struct device_node` pointer from a phandle.| <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_get_named_gpio()                | Gets a GPIO number to use in GPIO API calls.              | <linux/of_gpio.h>                 |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_find_property()                 | Checks if a property exists and returns the property.     | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_device_is_available()           | Checks if the device is available for use (not disabled). | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_get_property()                  | Retrieves a property value from a device node.            | <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_match_node()                    | Matches a device node against an array of compatible strings.| <linux/of.h>                      |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| of_address_to_resource()           | Extracts resource information from the device tree.       | <linux/of_address.h>              |
+------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------+

These APIs allow kernel modules and drivers to access and use the data specified in the device tree effectively, 
facilitating device initialization and configuration based on hardware descriptions. 

For developers working on drivers that interface with hardware described in device trees, 
understanding these APIs is crucial for effective driver implementation and system stability.



